@matthieusieben I think it could only be a "SHOULD" and not a "MUST" at best. So:

> `client_uri` SHOULD be a prefix of `client_id`

Unless the "client metadata document as a service" server has some way of generating a page for `client_uri`? Or we make it a MUST but allow for omission of the `client_uri`?

@matthieusieben the way we did this at Inrupt for working on Solid apps was to host a client_id at a temporary publicly accessible URL.

The other option is using something that exposes your localhost server to the public internet (which I'd not really recommend)

The reason for this is that the Authorization Server cannot access a localhost URL (without requesting to itself), so the URL of the client_id must resolve to a publicly accessible resource

```suggestion
## Client ID Metadata Documents for Development Purposes {#documents_for_development}
```

@ThisIsMissEm - the PR only builds on the private_key_jwt example and tries to bridge the gap. The idea was to allow existing credentials (certs, jwts etc) that contain identifiers that are not URLs to be used with this scheme (K8S PSAT, SPIFFE IDs, proprietary provisioned creds).... so the idea is to find a way to allow those to be used with this registration scheme....

Having said that, I don't love the special casing either ;).

I think there may also be other solutions to this problem, outside of the spec (e.g. workloads can engage with some kind of token exchange service to obtain a credential with a sub (JWT) or SAN (X.509) that contains a URL as opposed to the original credenitial it obtained. The downside is ofcourse that now client have to manage multiple credentials - they do badly with one, now they have two - but it may be a practical alternative (and better than having a special case on processing).
